04722nam a22006975i 9783111342931DE-B159720240306015011.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20232024gw     fo  d z      eng d  a97831113429317 a10.1515/97831113429312doi  a(DE-B1597)665478  a(OCoLC)1414457669  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  agwcDE04a9301 aNash, John, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aRulers of the Sea :bMaritime Strategy and Sea Power in Ancient Greece, 550–321 BCE /cJohn Nash. 1aMünchen ;aWien : bDe Gruyter Oldenbourg, c[2023] 4c©2024  a1 online resource (XII, 270 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aDe Gruyter Studies in Military History ,x2701-5629 ;v800tFrontmatter -- tNotes on spelling, names, and translations -- tAcknowledgements -- tContents -- tIntroduction: ‘sea power’ and other concepts -- tChapter One Setting the scene: geography, environment, navigation, and fishing -- tChapter Two Wooden walls: ships and naval organisation -- tChapter Three The ship of state: Greek maritime consciousness -- tChapter Four The birth of navies – sixth-century Greece -- tChapter Five Divine Salamis: the Persian Wars -- tChapter Six Rulers of the sea: Athens and the Delian League -- tChapter Seven The great war: the Peloponnesian war from Corcyra to Sicily -- tChapter Eight The triumph of sea power: Sicily and the Ionian War -- tChapter Nine No easy thing: the fall of Spartan sea power and Athens’ return -- tChapter Ten Aegean awakening: Thebes, war in the North, and the rise of Macedon -- tChapter Eleven The lessons of sea power -- tConclusion -- tAppendix 1 Glossary of terms -- tAppendix 2 Database of maritime operations -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThis is a study of sea power and maritime strategy in the Classical Greek world. More than just a study of navies and battles, it examines how the sea was used to influence events ashore and how the use of naval power combined with land power had a defining impact on the period. After an examination of the oft-overlooked practical issues of navigation and administration, the book explores the idea of a ‘maritime consciousness’ in Greece and how this shaped the way the Greeks engaged in war. Naval operations from the Persian Wars down to the rise of Thebes are examined at the operational and strategic level, including a catalogue of the hundreds of different maritime operations from the 5th and 4th centuries BCE. Further, while the great sea power Athens is most prominent, it looks at other city-states to examine how they utilised sea power. This new approach uses modern theory to highlight some enduring lessons of sea power. It demonstrates that Classical scholars should embrace sea power as an important concept in the Greek world. Modern scholars of naval and strategic studies should cast their gaze further back in time when looking for lessons in sea power. This book helps to bridge the scholarship between these two disciplines.  aIssued also in print.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 4aAltertumswissenschaften. 4aAntike. 4aMarinegeschichte. 4aMilitärgeschichte.  aAncient Greek.  aMilitary history.  aSea Power.  anaval history.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDG Plus DeG Package 2024 Part 1z97831113321920 cEPUBz97831113431670 cprintz978311134285640uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978311134293140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9783111342931423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9783111342931/original  a978-3-11-133219-2  DG Plus DeG Package 2024 Part 1b2024  aEBA_CL_CL  aEBA_CL_HICS  aEBA_DGALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_CL  aEBA_ECL_HICS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_SSH